The wake-up call came during my third week when one of our newer Sprinter vans started making a grinding noise on the way back from Eagle County Airport. The driver radioed in, and I told him to finish the run since it was probably just brake pad wear. When the van rolled into our maintenance bay two hours later, I discovered the brake rotor had cracked completely through. We were maybe twenty miles from a catastrophic brake failure on a mountain highway with eight passengers aboard.

That incident taught me something crucial about private shuttle safety measures. The real protection systems aren't the obvious ones that companies advertise. They're the behind-the-scenes protocols that prevent problems before they become emergencies. Most passengers focus on things like airbags and seat belts, which matter, but they're your last line of defense. The safety measures that actually keep you alive happen in maintenance bays and dispatch centers, places customers never see.

